{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514582","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514582"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:24:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:24:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12339"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12339","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12339"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.53,0.03,0.3,0.09,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4859"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55140"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4859","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4859"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12339"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40658"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"115"},{"type":"tags","id":"2840"},{"type":"tags","id":"2899"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7844"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9706"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15619"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43319"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55140","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55140"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 50-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with recurring episodes of pain and stiffness primarily in her finger joints, which are more pronounced in the morning and last for about 15 minutes. She also experiences shortness of breath, a cough and fatigue, particularly after exposure to cold. Additionally, she notices pallor in the skin of her fingers during these cold episodes. She has a medical history of hypertension, which is well-controlled with medication. She does not take any other regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 80/min, blood pressure 120/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Cardiovascular examination reveals normal heart sounds with no murmurs, rubs, or gallops. Respiratory examination reveals fine inspiratory crackles at the lung bases. She has tenderness and swelling primarily in the finger joints, and to a lesser extent in the wrists, elbows, and knees. The range of motion in the affected joints is limited. Her fingers are puffy with thickening and tightening of the skin. The skin on her arms up to her axillae is firm with areas of subtle increase and decrease in pigment. No evidence of ulcers or telangiectasia is observed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Diffuse systemic sclerosis","Antiphospholipid syndrome","CREST syndrome","Sine scleroderma","Overlap syndrome"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBased on the patient\u0027s symptoms and examination findings, the most likely diagnosis is \u003Cstrong\u003EDiffuse systemic sclerosis\u003C/strong\u003E. This condition is characterized by widespread vascular dysfunction and progressive fibrosis of the skin and internal organs. The patient\u0027s presentation aligns with this diagnosis due to several key features:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E1. Skin changes: The thickening and tightening of skin on the fingers and arms extending proximal to the elbows is characteristic of diffuse systemic sclerosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E2. Joint involvement: The recurring joint pain and morning stiffness, primarily affecting the fingers but also involving larger joints, are common in systemic sclerosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E3. Raynaud\u0027s phenomenon: The patient\u0027s description of finger pallor during cold exposure is consistent with Raynaud\u0027s phenomenon, a hallmark of systemic sclerosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E4. Respiratory symptoms: The shortness of breath, cough, and fine inspiratory crackles at the lung bases suggest potential interstitial lung disease, a common complication of systemic sclerosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntiphospholipid syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with recurrent venous or arterial thrombosis and pregnancy morbidity. While it can have diverse manifestations, the absence of thrombotic events and the presence of significant skin changes make this diagnosis less likely in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECREST syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is a limited form of systemic sclerosis characterized by calcinosis, Raynaud\u0027s phenomenon, esophageal dysfunction, sclerodactyly, and telangiectasia. While some features overlap with this patient\u0027s presentation, the extensive skin involvement and respiratory symptoms are more consistent with diffuse systemic sclerosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESine scleroderma\u003C/strong\u003E is a subtype of systemic sclerosis where patients exhibit internal organ involvement without apparent skin changes. This diagnosis is unlikely given the significant skin thickening observed in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOverlap syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E refers to a condition where a patient exhibits features of multiple connective tissue diseases. While this patient does have features that could be seen in various rheumatological conditions, the presentation is most consistent with a single diagnosis of diffuse systemic sclerosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETo confirm the diagnosis, further investigations would be warranted, including antinuclear antibody (ANA) testing, which is positive in approximately 95% of patients with systemic sclerosis. Specific autoantibodies such as anti-Scl-70 (anti-topoisomerase I) are associated with diffuse systemic sclerosis and a higher risk of severe interstitial lung disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Diffuse systemic sclerosis is characterised by skin thickening proximal to the elbows and knees, along with joint pain, Raynaud\u0027s phenomenon, and potential internal organ involvement.","Respiratory symptoms and fine inspiratory crackles at the lung bases can indicate interstitial lung disease in systemic sclerosis.","Antinuclear antibodies (ANA) are present in approximately 95% of patients with systemic sclerosis."],"references":["Adigun R, Goyal A, Hariz A. Systemic Sclerosis. In: StatPearls [Online]. Updated 2022 May 8. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430875/","Kowalska-K\u0119pczy\u0144ska A. Systemic Scleroderma-Definition, Clinical Picture and Laboratory Diagnostics. J Clin Med. 2022 Apr 20;11(9):2299. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC9100749/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40658"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12339"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40658","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40658"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-13T20:23:05+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-13T20:24:13+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4859"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55140"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":